group.name: I Love UBC Pit Night
group.description: Have you ever gotten blackout drunk in the middle of the week? Then you've probably experienced Pit Night Wednesday at UBC. This is for all the people who know and love the Pit (and pit night) (From the AMS website) In 1968, UBC's Associate Professor of Zoology David Suzuki declared "What this campus needs is a pub!" He received full support from the AMS President (former Minister of Forests) David Zirnhelt, and between the two of them, the Pit Pub was born....well, sort of. For five years it continued to be operated out of the SUB ballroom on the second floor, much like a beer garden. In January of 1969, the Ubyssey described the Pit as "a place to relax, eat a sandwich, and talk about the revolution...". In the fall of 1971 the most popular beers were Old Style, Uncle Ben's, Labatt Blue, and Heidelberg. There were complaints about the the price of beer being increased from 35 cents to 40 cents, and talk of adding a jukebox and a colour TV. Everybody wanted hot food and was hoping the Pit could start to provide burgers and fries. In January of 1973, the Ubyssey reported on plans for building the new Pit Pub in the SUB basement and by April of that year, construction began, with hopes to be in their new home by September of 1973. Unfortunately, there were delays and the new Pit didn't open officially until November 19, 1973. And this year, the Pit will celebrate its 36th birthday. The Pit continues to be the number one bar on campus and continues to feature student friendly pricing.

group.description: This link contains our rules. Please read it before joining: http://www.facebook.com/groups/9972923762/doc/10150257548193763/ "Legal and social discrimination against atheists in some places may lead some to deny or conceal their atheism due to fears of persecution. A 2006 study by researchers at the University of Minnesota involving a poll of 2,000 households in the United States found atheists to be the most distrusted of minorities, more so than Muslims, recent immigrants, gays and lesbians, and other groups. Many of the respondents associated atheism with immorality, including criminal behaviour, extreme materialism, and elitism." -Wikipedia, Demographics of Atheism, Discrimination "A 1995 survey attributed to the Encyclopædia Britannica indicates that the non-religious are about 14.7% of the world's population, and atheists around 3.8%. Another survey attributed to Britannica shows the population of atheists at around 2.4% of the world's population." -Wikipedia, Demographics of atheism, Distribution "Furthermore, atheists may not report themselves as such, to prevent suffering from social stigma, discrimination, and persecution in certain regions. Despite these problems, most studies indicate that the non-religious make up about 12-15% of the world's population." -Wikipedia, Demographics of atheism This group isn't afraid of the social stigma that comes from being a non-believer in irrational faith in a world too full of faith. Typically, atheism is reported so low in the media that you wouldn't know we existed, and most of the time when one or more of us is outed, there is sort of a social haze that develops in place. We're not creatures from the abyss to feared, we're human beings, just like every Christian, Muslim, or otherwise out there. The only difference is our title bears no single entity over us, and never will. If you're an atheist, join this group. You're not alone, and the world needs a wakeup call that we're your next-door neighbors, we're your firemen, police officers, insurance salesmen (let's leave that one out, though), doctors, lawyers, scientists, government officials, nerds, geeks, gamers, gamblers and otherwise!

Most fuel comes from the same source but if we target the major corporations and give our business to the smaller, independent stations indefinitely we may see a change. Ten years ago you could fill up your entire tank for under 30 dollars. Now we're lucky to get a half a tank for 30 dollars. Many people are burning up their paychecks before they even get to work. We can take a stand! Major stations to Boycott Indefinitely: Petro-Canada Esso Shell Husky -> INVITE ALL THE PEOPLE YOU KNOW FROM ONTARIO. Why RED? Because red is the color of emergency. More than 5,000 die every day and many more others are fighting for their lives; this is an emergency Brief overview: An estimated 33 million people around the world are currently living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) or acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS). In 2007, 2,000,000 people around the world died from AIDS. Since 1990, the number of people living with HIV has risen from 8,000,000 to 33,000,000 and 67% of the people currently living with HIV are located in sub-Saharan Africa. This number is still growing! Help raise awareness for World AIDS Day and World AIDS Week (Nov. 17th to 21th) at UBC - just by wearing RED. This is a campus wide event. No matter what year or what faculty you are in, help raise awareness about HIV/AIDS worldwide by wearing RED! **Note: Although World AIDS Day is officially scheduled around the world as December 1st, we at UBC rescheduled the date and prolonged it to a week long event (17-21) as to avoid conflicts with final exams in December. ------------------------------------------ | *INVITE ALL YOUR FRIENDS!!!* | ------------------------------------------

event.name: Puppetry of the Penis
event.description: Puppetry of the Penis Sunday, October 25, 2009 Centre for Performing Arts, 777 Homer St., Vancouver Doors 7:00pm - Showtime 8:00pm Tickets: $45.50/$39.50/$35.50 + s/c Available at: All Ticketmaster locations, by phone (604) 280-4444 or online at www.ticketmaster.ca WARNING: THIS IS A NON-SEXUAL SHOW AND INVOLVES FULL FRONTAL NUDITY (18+ Only I.D. Required) Puppetry of the Penis website: www.puppetryofthepenis.com Puppetry of the Penis was born when Simon Morley teamed up with fellow puppeteer David Friend. Their first show at the 1998 Melbourne International Comedy Festival was a huge hit and won recognition as the "Outright Best Show." The name 'Puppetry of the Penis' was originally conceived by Simon Morley, as the title of a highbrow art calendar. Released in 1997, the calendar showcased twelve of Simon's favorite penis installations (known as "Dick Tricks"). Years before, Simon's youngest brother, Justin, had shown him his first installation - 'The Hamburger'. Natural sibling rivalry resulted in the evolution of a grand repertoire of genital gesticulations. It was on New Year's Eve in 1997, with a garage full of calendars to sell and burgeoning requests for live demonstrations that prompted Simon to team up with David "Friendy" Friendy and unleash their talents on the world. Friendy had already been keeping himself busy for most of the year, having created a solid business performing his repertoire of installations at Batchelorette/Hen's night's and private parties. As a young boy, Friendy began his Dick Trick career in the bath and developed his skills further when he discovered beer in college. After completing his degree in computing, he returned to Melbourne with his own highly individual collection of hanging art. Together, Simon and Friendy's solo "acts" became Puppetry of the Penis, and a global phenomenon was born. Their debut at the 1998 Melbourne International Comedy Festival was a huge hit, kicking off an eight-month tour of Australia. The national tour covered 20,000 kilometers and was been captured in the documentary, Tackle Happy. Subsequent sell-out runs in Sydney and Melbourne encouraged the boys to take their wares to the 2000 Edinburgh International Fringe Festival, where they were humbled by yet another sell-out run. When a West End producer realized the potential of the show (after attending a performance where the woman sitting next to him wet her pants laughing), the world was no longer safe from the 'Art of Genital Origami'! Contracts and mops were brought out, and a deal was made on the spot: Puppetry of the Penis was on its way to London's West End. Initially booked for a five-week run at London's Whitehall Theatre, the overwhelming response led to numerous extensions. The show finally closed after an astonishing five-month run. Simon and Friendy became the darlings of the West End, delighting London's A-list including Hugh Grant, Naomi Campbell, Elton John, Bono and The Beckhams. In September 2001, on the heels of a smash hit run in Toronto and a successful tour of Canada, Puppetry of the Penis opened in New York at the John Houseman Theatre, where it played for nearly 2 years. By 2002 a second and third American company opened at LA's Coronet Theatre and San Francisco's Theatre on the Square. These two productions plus the international companies highlighted 2002 as being the phenomenal year when eight companies started playing simultaneously worldwide. The year was capped off by a memorable appearance on The Tonight Show with Jay Leno, which was one of the highest rating shows of the year. The Puppetry of the Penis juggernaut continued to gain momentum, with Simon and Friendy parting ways (temporarily) in 2003 and 2004 to focus on conquering both the USA and Europe simultaneously. During this period Puppetry of the Penis was translated into Mexican, Spanish and French! 2004 also saw Friendy and Simon reunited for a second West End Season, this time at The Apollo Theatre on Shaftesbury Avenue. After five years touring the world and successes from The West End to Broadway, it was time for the boys to come home and hang up their capes. In 2005 they launched their So Long tour and prepared to say good bye. Little did they realize that Australia had not finished with them yet and they subsequently toured Australia extensively throughout 2006 and 2007 doing the Resurrection tour. Puppetry of the Penis has performed at the Edinburgh Fringe Festival for 8 consecutive years, consistently selling out the prestigious Debating Hall at the Gilded Balloon! As of today most of the Western World has played host to Puppetry of the Penis including Australia, the UK, the USA, Germany, USA, Ireland, Scotland, New Zealand, Canada, Belgium, The Netherlands, Italy, Portugal, Norway, Argentina and Switzerland. 2008 brought the boys to a Decade of Dick - or as they like to say 'A Dickade'! Due to popular demand Simon and Friendy are still taking the penis to the people with performances this year in all Australian States ans Territories, USA, the UK, South Africa, and are now setting up bookings in Canada for 2009/2010.

event.description: Galeria Autonomica Eröffnung in München für 48 Stunden. Ort: Reichenbachstraße 38, am Gärtnerplatz Datum: 14.01.2010 und 15.01.2010 Beginn: 18.00h Am 14. Januar 2010 ist die Vernissage um 18:00 Uhr zur Austellung "Kampfsporthose mit Bündchen, Kulturrevolution" in der 48h Galeria Autonomica, Reichenbachstraße 38 im Glockebachvirrrtll! Nach genau 48 Stunden wird die Galerie genauso schnell geschlossen wie sie eröffnet wurde! Im Münchner Untergrund findet man jetzt richtige Kunstaktivisten! Gerade hat die Galeria Autonomica erst auf der Kunstmesse „Stroke01" sich in München präsentiert und schon kommen die Galeristen Christoph Pankowski und Christian Minke im Januar nach München zurück. Diesmal mieten die beiden jungen Galeristen Pankowski und Minke in München einen leerstehenden Laden mitten im Glockenbachviertel. Kurzentschlossen verwirklichen die beiden Kulturschaffenden Ihr neues Projekt „Galeria Autonomica for 48 h" Innerhalb von wenigen Jahren haben die beiden Kulturschaffenden ein weltweites Künstlernetzwerk aufgebaut, somit können wir uns auf Künstler u.a. aus New York, München, Paris, Leipzig, Kassel, Gießen und Fulda freuen. Die kleine Produzentengalerie ist zugleich auch eine Pilotengalerie denn die Galeristen möchten Künstlern eine Plattform abseits des Mainstream in der Galerien-Szene bieten. Ihre festgehaltenen künstlerischen und gestalterischen Strömungen sei es in Bildern, Skulpturen, Videos, Musik sowie Installationen zu präsentieren, jedmögliche Art von künstlerischem Ausdruck einem alternativen Publikum öffentlich zu machen. Diesmal in München, aber nur für 48 Stunden. Pankowski:"Wir bemühen uns stets unser Qualitätslevel zu steigern und sind permanent auf Künstlersuche!" Mittlerweile jagt ein Event das andere, unterwegs von Stadt zu Stadt versuchen sie Kunstrichtungen wie beispielsweise Graffiti und Street Art ins Bewusstsein der Bevölkerung zu rücken. Gegründet wurde die Galerie 2008. Die beiden wilden Avantgarde-Galeristen wollen jungen Künstlern eine Plattform bieten, deren Ästhetiken vielleicht im Untergrund etabliert, im Herz des Kunstbetriebs jedoch längst nicht anerkannt sind. Der Galerist und Künstler Minke: "Wir wollen Künstler zeigen, die seit Jahren oder gar Jahrzehnten im Untergrund aktiv sind. Wir wollen ihnen den Zugang zum Kunstmarkt ermöglichen und bei jeder Ausstellung die verschiedenen Strömungen, meist gleichen Ursprungs, in einem elektrizistischen Neben- und Miteinander von Gestiken und Motiven, präsentieren. Wer die Kulturrevolution in München nicht verpassen will, der muss vom 14.-15.01.2010 in der Reichenbachstraße 38 vorbei schauen! Die Galerie wird 48 Stunden Ihre Türen offen lassen! event.name: Awards Night and Recognition HIRING Executives!
event.description: Hello Sauderites! The Awards Night and Recognition Committee serve to recognize individuals with significant contributions to the Commerce Undergraduate Society. If you answered yes to the above questions, then you should definitely consider applying for the Awards Night and Recognitions Committee. Awards and Recognitions Committee (7 positions open) Positions Available VP Finance - To aid the Awards Night and Recognitions Coordinator (ANRC) in managing the budget, and overseeing all reimbursements VP Marketing -Work with ANRC/Entertainment Coordinator to oversee production of visual media, AV, promotional material and invitations for Awards Night VP Logistics -Contact external organizations for Awards Night needs, work with ANRC/VP Marketing to oversee the operations of the Awards Night, as well as creating a floor plan Entertainment Coordinator -Search and coordinate entertainment for Awards Night to ensure a successful event. Recognitions Coordinator (2) -Manage the evaluation of Top Club Award and the Teaching Excellence Award (joint duties) -Responsible for aiding the ANRC in determining how the Top Club and Teaching Excellence awards will be evaluated and selected. Awards Night Coordinator -Aid with the planning Awards Night Ceremony to recognize individuals who have contributed to the Commerce Undergraduate Society. General Responsibilities for all committee members: -Going to club events and evaluating their performance, the degree of student attendance and satisfaction. -Develop clear guidelines on how the Top Club and Teaching Excellence Awards will be evaluated. -Conducting surveys and issuing evaluations for students to complete as research in making recommendations for who the winners are. -Determine a venue, event schedule, event theme and decorations -Decide upon the service award levels, the appearance of awards and how many are distributed -Order and ensure the punctual preparation of awards -Facilitate in the overall execution of the Awards Night, take on miscellaneous tasks to ensure event success What skills/attributes do I need? -Dedication, enthusiasm, time commitment and diligence -Solid decision-making skills and organizational skills -creativity and team-oriented -Website design, AV, design (Adobe Photoshop, InDesign), or video production skills a definite asset -Previous involvement with Awards Night or event coordination can be an asset as well What will I get out of it? -The chance to get involved in the CUS by attending club events for free and evaluating their performance -A voice in determining how the top two awards are evaluated -The chance to get involved in the CUS by assessing professor performance and reflecting student body opinion -An opportunity to meet new people by participating in an interactive committee -Experience in decision making and event coordination -An opportunity to be a part of creating one of the most unforgettable nights of 2011 -Making amazing memories with an amazing team!! Requirements 1. Cover Page a. Name, Year b. Major / Intended Major c. Rank your top two choices for positions 2. Cover Letter: (Guidelines) a. Why do you want to be a part of the Awards Night and Recognitions Committee? b. What is your vision for your position in the upcoming year? c. Where do you want to see Awards Night held next year? 3. Up-to-date Resume All applications must be sent to Alice Huang and Angie Yao at alice.yc.huang@gmail.com and yao.angelica.gmail.com Deadline: Monday, April 12th @ 11:59pm. We will contact you via e-mail to arrange for interview times. Should you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to contact us (Alice and Angie). We look forward to seeing your applications! Sincerely, Alice and Angie Awards Night and Recognition Co-Chairpersons

event.name: Petition to investigate road safety on Gaglardi Way
event.description: LINK: https://spreadsheets.google.com/viewform?formkey=dHdRYy1xbGFLYlZwNjVLM25BMGFYZlE6MQ ____ JL: If you're objecting simply because 'other' drivers are 'stupid', thanks but this is getting annoying. Just remember that some accidents are multi-vehicle and sometimes innocent people are involved. So what's wrong with keeping the innocent people safe? It's the next best thing to removing stupid drivers. And on that point - I have no confidence of being able to change. Go talk to the Minister of Transportation if you want the licensing laws revised. http://www.gov.bc.ca/tran/contacts.html ____ Please allow me to clarify. Brake fade does NOT equal brake wear. No, quite frankly, I don't care if you spend more money on brakes (brake wear). What brake FADE is when you lose braking power after overheating the brakes. You can usually overheat the brakes by either by applying the brakes for an extended period of time, or by applying heavy braking multiple times within a short timespan. To avoid this, you should only brake occasionally as needed to keep a safe speed, so that by the time you need to make the tight turn at the bottom of Gaglardi (or avoid something...), you will actually have brakes. If your brakes are overheated during an emergency, pressing the brake pedal doesn't do anything. In that case, you would want barriers. Or perhaps you might prefer to hug trees. Source: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brake_fade ___________________________ ___________________________ Every few months, a fatal car accident occurs on the main route up to SFU, Gaglardi Way. Just some examples: • http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bicet5u7oXQ • http://www.vancouversun.com/news/Students+Burnaby+residents+stranded+Burnaby+Mountain+closed/3845660/story.html • http://www.theprovince.com/news/vancouver/Young+woman+killed+Burnaby+crash/4406549/story.html The roadway is currently ranked #5 on the list of BC's top crash locations with 240 crashes per year. I see a number of factors contributing to this: • Steep descent causes high speed travel of all vehicles, including buses and large trucks. But constantly braking is not advisable as that will cause brake fade • Unrealistic speed limit of 60km/h The downhill average is closer to 100km/h so the odd car that follows the speed limit can become a hazard • Lack of streetlamps to illuminate the road Especially when Vancouver rains so often and Burnaby Mountain is more prone to black ice and freezing rain than other places in Metro Vancouver • Lack of central dividers and crash barriers on shoulder on the downhill direction If there is a loss of control for any reason or a need to evade a hazard (deer, slowed/stopped car, etc.), one can either enter opposing traffic or crash down the cliff As I am not an expert in highway safety, nor am I pretending to be one, I am petitioning the City of Burnaby and the SFU administration to have professionals assess the feasibility of installing crash barriers, dividers, streetlamps, and/or other safety measures to improve road safety, especially at night. I will be sending a letter to the Office of the Board of Governors, City of Burnaby and ICBC - please join me in this cause by entering your name in the form below. If you would like an electronic copy of the letter, please also enter your email address. Your email address will not appear on the letter. https://spreadsheets.google.com/viewform?formkey=dHdRYy1xbGFLYlZwNjVLM25BMGFYZlE6MQ

event.name: "Message Mob" - Elections Canada responds, now, let's get out and vote!
event.description: *** LAST CHANCE TO VOTE! - POLLS ARE STILL OPEN FOR ANOTHER FEW HOURS *** Go to http://www.leadnow.ca/vote-social and rally your friends to the polls! **************** On Thursday April 14th, the Conservative Party of Canada mounted a legal challenge to disqualify the votes of hundreds of students at the University of Guelph. The next day, Elections Canada stated that the votes were valid, but that further special ballots would not be permitted in this election. Leadnow.ca, Anna, and many of you, were concerned that shutting down special ballots on campus would unnecessarily limit students' ability to exercise their democratic right and vote. We hoped that, by communicating with Elections Canada, we could resolve any outstanding issues relating to party oversight of these special ballots so students could vote on campus this election. We have communicated with Elections Canada on behalf of all of you, and learned the following: * Past special ballot collection points at Guelph were not authorized centrally by the Chief Electoral Officer, although they should have been. * No further special ballot collection points on campus were planned for this election, and therefore none were shut down as a result of this controversy. Further, it is not possible at this last minute to organize special ballots on campuses for this election. Prior to this election, Elections Canada developed service standards to make registration and voting processes more accessible to student voters in consultation with student organizations such as the Canadian Alliance of Student Associations. See those standards here: http://www.elections.ca/res/pub/ecdocs/EC10047_e.pdf Elections Canada has now committed to reviewing student voting initiatives following this election, and, in consultation with all interested stakeholders, identify what service improvements could be initiated to improve the convenience of voting for students. For more information on how you can vote in this election, go to http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=vot&dir=yth/bas/faq&document=index&lang=e#a5 We thank Elections Canada for their time and hard work, and Leadnow.ca will work with them to help make voting as accessible as possible for all students in the future. Thank you for reading this message and being ready to take action to support student voting. Let's get out there and vote together! http://www.leadnow.ca/en/vote-mobs

event.name: Cinema Politica UBC - H2Oil
event.description: What is more important, Oil or Water? A month after the UN Climate Change Conference in Durban where Canada failed to advocate for clean energy solutions, and in the midst of controversy over the negotiations of the construction of the Keystone XL oil pipeline, Cinema Politica will be screening the film H2Oil. This Canadian documentary looks at the problems associated with water and oil on the Alberta tar sands, and the actions being taken to counter the negative impacts of oil sands extraction. Synopsis: America's biggest oil supplier has become Canada's oil sands. The process of oil sands extraction uses up to 4 barrels of water to produce one barrel of crude oil. It goes without saying that water -- its depletion, exploitation, privatization and contamination -- has become the most important issue to face humanity in this century. At the same time, the war for oil is well underway across the globe. A struggle is increasingly being fought between water and oil, not only over them. Alberta's oil sands are at the centre of this tension. In only a few short years, North America will be a crisscross of pipelines, leaving toxic water basins the size of Lake Ontario, and surface-mines as large as Florida. H2Oil follows a voyage of discovery, heartbreak and politicization in the stories of those attempting to defend water in Alberta against tar sands expansion. With hope and courage H2Oil tells the story of one of the most significant, and destructive projects of our time. Trailer: http://www.cinemapolitica.org/film/h2oil Cinema Politica UBC is a series showcasing documentaries that critically engage in urgent social justice, environmental, economic and gender issues. We believe film is a powerful tool for social change, and are committed to presenting alternative points of view, supporting independent and local filmmakers, and creating a space for discussion and engagement. The films show every second Tuesday at 7pm in the Norm Theatre of the UBC Student Union Building. All screenings are by donation and open to the public - students as well as members of the community. Join our Facebook page or follow us on Twitter (docsUBC) to stay in the loop.

event.name: WACHU CONCERT SERIES 16
event.description: INTRODUCING $1.79 CARIBOO BEERS @ WACHU!! Has music ever sent a chill down your spine? Have you ever NEEDED to tell someone else about a great performance you saw? Do you love the fact that you can't ever explain live music to anyone because words will never do it justice? If you said yes to any of the above, you will be excited to know that there is another great opportunity coming your way for you to see some of Vancouver's best musical talent. THE SHOW: July 11, Electric Owl 926 Main St. $10 Tickets at the door Buy online and save! www.wachu.org Online: $8 each, 3 for $7.50 each, 5 for $7 each $1.79 Cariboo Beers all night! Doors at 8pm, show at 9pm EXTRA TREATS -Everyone gets a free music download card containing tracks from each artist -$2 CARIBOOS all night long! -Discount code for print media including business cards and more from our sponsor, Clubcard www.clubcard.ca -Everyone can get a free 8-day gym pass to Steve Nash fitness world and a chance to win a 3-month all-inclusive pass www.stevenashfitnessclubs.com THE ARTISTS: The Ruffled Feathers www.theruffledfeathers.com A chamber rock band from Vancouver Canada, The Ruffled Feathers are known for their combination of haunting female vocals, carefully crafted harmonies, instrumentation, and brazen horns. Taking inspiration from the likes of Beirut, The Arcade Fire, and Belle and Sebastian, the band weaves fables of revolution, love stories, and cities away from home. Listeners expecting conventional guitar-driven indie-pop will find themselves swept into complex arrangements of trumpets and mandolins instead. The Oh Wells www.theohwells.com The Oh Wells are a quirky, high energy indie pop band with a lot of heart. Pianist Sarah Jickling began writing her first songs as a highschool student, inspired by the growing pains of being a teenager. Four years later, Sarah and her band have released an EP length album entitled "Not that Girl From transformers", featuring songs about everything from dance clubs to children's books. Bloggers for the Vancouver Music Review described the group precisely as "Tegan and Sara banter put into song mixed with all the awkwardness that makes Arrested Development amazing with a dash of Pheobe from Friends". The Oh Wells have won first place in Citr's Shindig!, snagged a top spot in Seattle's Soundoff! Finals, and were a part of the Peak Performance Project top twenty. They have just returned from their first Canadian Tour. Ashleigh Eymann www.ashleigheymann.com Ashleigh Eymann is anything but a one-trick-pony. Fusing blues, hip-hop, jazz and folk, this Vancouver born songstress pushes perimeters, delivering a funky hybrid of soul music. The roles of emcee, vocalist, and multi-instrumentalist are here guns blazing and passionately wrapped up in one chick. Enjoy.

event.name: Spannungsverhältnis - eine Kunstausstellung
event.description: Soziale Netzwerke und Vereinsamung, Liebe und Hass, Regen und Sonnenschein, Individuum und Gesellschaft. Die Welt ist ein einziges Spannungsverhältnis. Davon, welche Gegensätze sie in ihrem Leben am stärksten bedrängen, begeistern und beschäftigen, erzählen die Künstler Michaela Herzog, Julian Schulz, Valentina Eppich, Florian Aigner, Veronika Dräxler und Fabian Bross in ihrer Ausstellung „Spannungsverhältnis", die vom 28.08. bis zum 03.09.2012 im Provisorium zu sehen sein wird. Michaela Herzog studiert Kunstpädagogik M.A. an der LMU München. Motive ihrer Bilder sind zum einen abstrakt gepunktete Buntstiftwolken, zum anderen alle möglichen Vertreter der Tierwelt, die mit Acrylfarbe und Holzstift handzahm zum Leben erweckt werden. Fabian Bross studiert Linguistik in München. Er ist Mitbegründer der Literaturzeitschrift „das Prinzip der sparsamstem Erklärung" und des Wissenschafts-Journals „Helikon". Seine Kunst beschäftigt sich mit dem Spannungsverhältnis zwischen Individuum und Gesellschaft und der Freiheit des Menschen. Mehr unter fabianbross.de Florian Aigner, passionierter Vogel-Strauß-Reiter, reist um die Welt und dokumentiert dies mit seiner Kamera. Die Aufnahmen von Landschaften, Städten und den Menschen, denen er begegnet, zeugen von der Intimität und Intensität seiner Erlebnisse. Valentina Eppich studiert Englische Literaturwissenschaft in München. In ihren Acrylgemälden beschäftigt sie sich in grellen Farben und oberflächlicher Leichtigkeit - an guten Tagen - primär mit Organen. Julian Schulz studierte Fotodesign in München. Seine Bilder bieten eine Mischung aus Dokumentation und Inszenierung, hyperrealer Darstellung und Reduktion. Man kann sich nie sicher sein ob das Dargestellte der Realität entspricht oder ausgedacht ist. Mehr unter julian-schulz.com Veronika Christine Dräxler mag keine Marmelade dafür aber Medien. Sie ist ausgebildete Museumspädagogin, studierte Kommunikationsdesignerin, im diesjährigen Mentoringprogramm des Presseclub Münchens, seit 2011 in der Klasse von Klaus vom Bruch an der Akademie der Bildenden Künste München und bloggt über Kunst, Kultur und Gesellschaft auf http://www.selbstdarstellungssucht.de/. Sie beschäftigt sich in ihren Arbeiten mit Persönlichkeiten, dem Internet und Unsinn, vorallem aber mit Letzterem.
